did.abstract: This collection contains the records of the High School Journalism Institute from 1947-2003. The Institute was formed to provide secondary students with the opportunity to learn about journalism by offering workshops in newspaper and yearbook publication. There are eight series in this collection: Scholarship and award files; Subject files; Administrative files; Faculty files; Newspaper files; Publications; Scrapbook files; and Photographs.

accessrestrict.head: Access Restrictions
accessrestrict.p: This collection is open for research.

bioghist.head: Administrative History
bioghist.p: The Indiana University High School Journalism Institute began in the summer of 1947 by serving as a continuing education program for secondary students and teachers from Indiana and beyond. The Institute is still offered to secondary students today. Run by the Indiana University School of Journalism, the Institute is held in Ernie Pyle Hall. It allows secondary students to participate in workshops over the course of five days in newspaper advising, web design, photo journalism, and/or yearbook advising.

When the Institute began in 1947, secondary students would spend two weeks on the Bloomington campus receiving training. The first summer had 47 students from 22 schools. The Institute peaked in 1960 with 570 participants. One-week sessions were also offered for interested students, but in the early 1990s the Institute dropped the two-week format and created five-day sessions. Students that are interested, however, can utilize the "stay-over" program offered by HSJI. This program allows students to attend one session, stay over the weekend, and attend the next session the following week. The Institute also offers one-day workshops for high school journalism faculty.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Organized into eight series: Administrative files; Publications; Subject files; Faculty files; Newspaper files; Scholarship and awards files; Scrapbook files; and Photographs.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Note
scopecontent.p: This collection contains eight series: Scholarship and awards files, Subject files, Administrative files, Faculty files, Newspaper files, Publications, Scrapbook files, and Photographs.

The first series contains Scholarship and awards files for 1947-1984. There are lists of award winners at the Institute from 1947-1982. There are also scholarship applications and information from 1953-1984. These applications were filled out by the students of the Institute and included their activities at their schools, where they hoped to attend college, and lists of their favorite authors and books. Also, in this file are notes from interviews with individuals who were awarded the scholarships. Important journalists, professors, and administrators were asked to speak at the award dinners, and their biographies are provided. The files cover the years 1947-1964. Examples of these speakers include James Hetherington, an Institute alumnus who was editor of WFBM stations in Indianapolis, and Herman B Wells, an alumnus, past president, and former chancellor of Indiana University. These records are all arranged chronologically.

The second series, Subject files, are arranged alphabetically and cover the years 1925-1984. Included in this series are advertisements for the Institute from 1950-1952, a history of the High School Journalism Institute, a directory of the high school journalism departments in Indiana for 1925, and articles written by Gordon "Bish" Thompson for the Evansville Press when he attended the Institute in 1965.

The records in the third series, Administrative files, cover the years from 1947-1985 and are arranged chronologically. Statistics of students that attended the Institute are given from 1947 to 1985. There is also correspondence from students to the program directors expressing interest in journalism and attending the program. The files also include programs from the opening convocations.

Faculty files make up the fourth series covering 1948-1999. Within this series is biographical information on instructors and visiting lecturers. These folders are listed alphabetically by the lecturer's last name. Gretchen Kemp, who served as Institute director until 1987, has a separate file of biographical information.

The fifth series, Newspaper files, contains clippings from 1959-1968. These newspaper clippings include information on Institute award winners and guest speakers, and also contain articles written by the students and pictures from the Institute. This file also contains news bureau releases about the Institute from 1964 to 1978.
Publications, the sixth series, consists of four sub-series: Guidebooks, Newsletters, Brochures, and Directories. The dates for these records range from 1947-2003.

The first sub-series, Guidebooks, were published to help students during their time at the Institute. Lists of rules, itineraries, and information are provided in the guidebooks. The guidebooks cover the period from 1980-1984.
The second sub-series, Newsletters, include those produced by the Institute's participants, such as The Sig, and The Informer, from 1949-1980.
The third sub-series, Brochures, were sent out to students, schools, and teachers to promote the Institute. Brochures for 1950-1984 can be found in this file, as well as registration forms.

The last sub-series, Directories, contain directories for 1947-2003. The directories list the students' and instructors' names, schools, and contact information. The directories are divided into each of the sessions for the given year.
The seventh series consists of Scrapbook files from 1949-1963. The scrapbooks contain newspaper clippings and photographs from the Institute sessions. Files are arranged chronologically.

The eighth series, Photographs, contains photographs and negatives from 1950-1985. A majority of these files are listed chronologically, but there are some undated photographs and negatives as well. The photographs are from the Institute sessions, and include group and individual photographs. These files are not housed with the rest of the collection, and can be accessed by contacting the University Archives staff.

relatedmaterial.head: Related Material
relatedmaterial.p: Other records relating to journalism at Indiana University can be found in the School of Journalism records, Collection 142.

userestrict.head: Usage Restrictions
userestrict.p: Copyrights for records originating with Indiana University administrative units, departments, and other offices are held by the Trustees of Indiana University. For more information, please contact the Indiana University Archives staff.

The Indiana University Archives respects the intellectual property rights of others and does not claim any copyrights for non-university records, materials in the public domain, or materials for which we do not hold a Deed of Gift. Responsibility for the determination of the copyright status of these materials rests with those persons wishing to reuse the materials. Researchers are responsible for securing permission from copyright owners and any other rights holders for any reuse of these materials that extends beyond fair use or other statutory limitations.

Digital reproductions of archival materials from the Indiana University Archives are made available for noncommercial educational and research purposes only. If you are the copyright holder for any of the digitized materials and have questions about its inclusion on our site, please contact the Indiana University Archivist.

appraisal.head: Appraisal
appraisal.p: Materials were pulled and discarded if there were more than three copies per Archives retention policy. Contracts of Institute lecturers were pulled and disposed of according to the Academic Personnel records retention schedule.
